cmes.note: Faint, narrow CME first seen to the East in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2026-01-20T06:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a C2.1 class flare which peaked at 2026-01-20T05:32Z from Active Region 14349 (S10E70) as seen in SDO AIA 131. Field line opening and a small amount of filament material can be seen in association with this flare in SDO AIA 193 and 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Narrow CME seen to the North by GOES CCOR-1 beginning at 2026-01-20T06:45Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. There is no clear source seen for this event as it likely originated from near/beyond the limb.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement due to unclear source location near the North limb. Measurement based on best fit in GOES CCOR-1 and SOHO LASCO C3.

cmes.note: Faint CME first seen to the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2026-01-20T08:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a very minor eruption seen in GOES SUVI 195 beginning at approx. 2026-01-20T07:22Z, located near Active Region 14349 (S14E68).

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2026-01-20T09:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This event is obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is a slow erupting filament seen along the South limb in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304 and is seen to the SW in STEREO A EUVI 304, suggesting a far sided source location. This filament begins to lift off at approx. 2026-01-20T07:28Z, but does not appear to leave the disk at approx. 2026-01-20T09:04Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Narrow CME seen to the North by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2026-01-20T12:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. There is no clear source seen for this event as it likely originated from near/beyond the limb.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit in GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the NE in GOES CCOR-1 starting at 2026-01-21T00:15Z. In real time, this CME was only seen in GOES CCOR-1 and was missed by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 due to real-time data gaps. The source of this CME is most likely far-sided. There is some field line movement from on/beyond the NE limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting as early as 2026-01-20T22:30Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement based on running difference imagery from GOES CCOR-1.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the west in GOES CCOR-1, SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. There is a data gap in SOHO LASCO imagery in real-time from 2026-01-21T08:24Z to 11:24Z. As such, the earliest frame of this event is not observed by SOHO LASCO imagery and this CME is only seen in SOHO LASCO coronagraphs following the data gap at 2026-01-21T11:24Z. The source for this event is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk around the time of this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. This event is blocked by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3 and is not seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to a data gap starting at 2026-01-21T16:08Z. The source may be related to dimming centered near N08W45 seen in SDO AIA 193 imagery starting around 2026-01-21T16:00Z but the source is unclear.

cmeAnalyses.note: A plane-of-sky measurement was made using a longitude of 90 degrees due to the uncertain source and data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery.

cmes.note: CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1. Not seen in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C3 in real-time due to a data gap. The source may be an eruption centered around N15W55, best seen as dimming starting at 2026-01-21T16:00Z in GOES SUVI 195. The eruption is not clearly visible in SDO imagery due to a spacecraft maneuver.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the potential source location using GOES CCOR-1 imagery.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2, although it starts notably faint in LASCO C2's field of view and is much better viewed in later frames of the other coronagraphs. The source is not clear, and could be associated with a small filament ejecta centered around S05W85, NW of AR 14343, in SDO AIA 193/304 starting around 2026-01-22T00:31Z, although swpc_cat triangulation reliably matches longitudes closer to W110-W115 around the limb. STEREO A EUVI imagery is in a data gap between 2026-01-21T16:15Z and 2026-01-22T03:15Z, so no far-sided source observations were possible.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 only, as the CME front is better observed in later frames.

cmes.note: CME observed to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and more NE in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely a filament eruption in the vicinity of AR 14352, with complex dimming following the ejecta. The filament began to brighten and eject starting around 2026-01-22T01:06Z in SDO AIA 304, spanning approximately N07W12 to S02W03 at this time. Two dimming regions follow this ejecta in SDO AIA 193, one centered around N05E15 (referenced as the source coordinates here) directly after the filament ejecta, and another further away centered around N15E30 starting around 2026-01-22T02:04Z which may be part of this CME front or a following outflow. Wide field line movement deflecting to the NNE in SDO AIA 171 follows this complex eruption.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the E only in STEREO A COR2. The source is uncertain, and could be outflow following CME 2026-01-22T02:36Z (sourced at N05E15).

cmeAnalyses.note: STEREO A plane-of-sky taken at E38.5 degrees, with STEREO A's current position at W51.5.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the N in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and NE in STEREO A COR2. The source is either continued outflow from CME: 2026-01-22T02:36Z or an area of dimming centered around N24E04 observed in SDO AIA 193 starting around 2026-01-22T04:00Z, although this dimming source appears unlikely to be associated due to the deflection.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the N in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and NE in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely a dimming region centered ~N24E04 observed starting around 2026-01-22T04:07Z in SDO AIA 193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the NE only in STEREO A COR2. The source for this CME is unclear and likely not observed on-disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: STEREO A plane-of-sky taken at E38.5 degrees, with STEREO A's current position at W51.5.

cmes.note: Faint CME first seen to the NE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2026-01-22T14:38Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a minor instance of dimming and field line opening seen located at approx. N40E05 and beginning at approx. 2026-01-22T12:51Z as seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1.

cmes.note: Faint CME observed to the NNE only in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, not in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source for this CME is unclear and likely not observed on-disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: SOHO LASCO C2 only plane-of-sky.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2026-01-22T18:12Z, as well as by GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which began at 2026-01-22T16:09Z, and is directed into the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this event is a filament eruption from along the NW limb (approx. N15W90). This eruption can be seen in SDO AIA 304 beginning around 2026-01-22T17:22Z, and lifting off at approx. 2026-01-22T17:56Z. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171 and 193. This source is not visible in STEREO A EUVI due to a data gap which began at 2026-01-22T15:45Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement using a longitude of W90 due to source near the limb and lack of STEREO A COR2 imagery to triangulate or STEREO A EUVI imagery to visually determine longitude.

cmes.note: Narrowish CME with messy front seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, following in the footsteps of CME: 2026-01-22T21:12Z. The CME is seen more clearly to NE in STEREO A COR2 after the nightly data gap ending at 2026-01-23T03:08Z. The front in STEREO is clear and bright in difference imagery, but there is also a fainter accompanying wider front as well in STEREO, possibly a very faint shock. The source could be a minor filament eruption seen after 2026-01-23T02Z centered around (N30E01), as seen in GOES SUVI 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit of the front with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2) and confirmed by the location of the likely source - a minor filament eruption centered (N30E01).

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the northeast in STEREO A COR2 imagery. This event is not observed by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 or GOES CCOR-1 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk that correspond with this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: A plane-of-sky measurement was made using a longitude of -39 degrees in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to the far-sided and therefore unknown source location. Additionally, this event is not visible in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 or GOES CCOR-1 imagery. A triangulated measurement is not available as a result.

cmes.note: Partial halo CME seen to the SSE in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1 coronagraphs and to the SW in STEREO A COR2. Its far-sided source could be indicated by the slowly unfolding prominence eruption seen behind the limb after 2026-01-23T11Z in the SE in SDO AIA 304 and 171 and GOES SUVI 304/284.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate 3D analysis based on the fit of the CME front with two coronagraphs (STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1) in the absence of SOHO LASCO imagery. The source is far-sided.

cmes.note: Narrow CME seen to the NE in GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2; not yet seen in SOHO LASCO (waiting for the downlink). Its source is likely a relatively minor eruption seen starting after 2026-01-23T14:57Z and centered (N15E20) in SDO AIA 193, with dimming and post eruptive arcades.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit of the front with two coronagraphs (STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1) and confirmed by the location of the likely source (minor filament eruption).

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. It is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source appears to be a filament eruption from beyond the SE limb as seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2026-01-23T15:48Z. Around the same time, faint moving/opening field lines are also visible to the SE in SDO/AIA 193/171 and GOES SUVI 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery with relation to the suspected source. Parameters may vary by +/- 10 degrees due to limited stereoscopic viewpoints.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the S/SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. It is not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to a data gap. The source appears to be a complex eruption stretching from well beyond the SE limb to the Earth-facing side of the disk. Starting around 2026-01-23T20:36Z there is a filament eruption with associated moving/opening field lines, EUV wave, and post-eruptive arcades as seen in SDO/AIA 193, 171, 211, 304, and GOES SUVI 284 and 304 imagery. Large deflection to the south is visible in initial SOHO LASCO C2 frames. It is unclear what the cause of this deflection is, but it may be due to nearby coronal holes. This CME overlaps the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2026-01-23T17:12Z which is associated with a similar portion of the filament eruption which may have helped trigger this complex eruption associated with this CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. The parameters may vary due to limited stereoscopic viewpoints.

cmes.note: Faint outflow/minor CME which is seen SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1, as well as directly S in STEREO A COR2. The start of the CME could be a bit earlier. No source has been found for this CME in EUV imagery, so it is likely far-sided.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis of this far-sided faint event based on the fit with three coronagraphs (STEREO A COR2, SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1). No source has been found in the EUV imagery to confirm this analysis.

cmes.note: Narrow faint CME seen to the NE in STEREO A COR2 and N in SOHO LASCO C2/GOES CCOR-1. Its source could be a relatively minor eruption just N of the northeastern coronal hole, centered ~(N15E10) which is seen starting around 2026-01-24T08:30Z in AIA 193 as dimming and post-eruptive arcades.

cmeAnalyses.note: Analysis based on the fit of the narrow front with two coronagraphs (STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C3). Very well corresponds to the likely source - an eruption from (N15E10), with significant northern deflection, likely due to a large coronal hole being just to the south of the eruption site.

cmes.note: Faint oblique front seen E in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and possibly very faint dimpled and messy front to the E in STEREO A COR2. This front is better seen in SOHO LASCO and CCOR-1 but either very faint/messy or not seen in STEREO A COR2. Its source is possibly the clear movement of field line(s) on/behind the E limb seen in AIA 171/193 starting after 2026-01-24T08:30Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: A very speculative, approximate measurement due to the faintness of the front in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph. This analysis is based on the fit of the front in three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). The source (moving field lines indicating a far-sided filament eruption) is either on or (more likely) behind the E limb.

cmes.note: Faint CME with a dimpled, messy front seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2, overlapping with a fainter, wider and messier front of CME:2026-01-24T09:24Z. Its source could be a very minor eruption/dimming seen around 2026-01-24T09:30Z around N05E80.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis of a faint dimpled front based on its fit with three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1).

cmes.note: Relatively bright CME first seen to SSW in STEREO A COR2 and then S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. There seem to be two or 3 lobes to it (or possibly 2 lobes and a fainter shock, but this is unclear). No EUV source has been found on disk, so the CME is far-sided. Source eruption far to the south, behind the limb is seen in GOES SUVI 284 as movement of field lines after 2026-01-24T10:30Z and more faintly in SDO AIA 193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate analysis of this far-sided CME, based on the fitting of the fronts seen in all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). Fitting is difficult because the CME consists of several lobes.

cmes.note: Narrow CME first seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2026-01-24T12:48Z. This front is also seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 and might be faintly seen to the SE in STEREO A COR2. There is no additional source signature for this CME, and it is most likely outflow following CME: 2026-01-24T09:24Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement chosen due to lack of source signature and lack of available triangulation.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2026-01-24T15:00Z. This front is also seen to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C3 and to the SW in STEREO A COR2 but is obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. There is no additional source signature for this CME, and it is most likely outflow following CME: 2026-01-24T10:53Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: Faint CME first seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2026-01-24T18:36Z. This front is also seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C3 and to the SSW for a single frame before a real-time data gap in STEREO A COR2. The CME is obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. There is no additional source signature for this CME, and it is most likely outflow following CME: 2026-01-24T10:53Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and a single frame from STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2026-01-24T20:00Z. CME is also seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1 and is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is most likely some far-sided field line movement seen beyond the E limb in SDO AIA 193 and SDO AIA 171 starting around 2026-01-24T19:00Z. There is some northward deflection later into propagation.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement chosen because the longitude of the source cannot be determined from coronal signatures, and triangulation is not available due to a real-time data gap in STEREO A COR2.

cmes.note: CME first seen to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2026-01-24T21:12Z. This front is also seen to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C3 but is obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1 and covered by a real-time data gap in STEREO A COR2. There is no additional source signature for this CME, and it is most likely outflow following CME: 2026-01-24T10:53Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement chosen because of the lack of coronal signatures and because only one perspective was available in real time.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the east in GOES CCOR-1, SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source may be related to an eruption visible over the eastern limb starting around 2026-01-25T05:15Z seen in SDO AIA 304 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

cmes.note: This CME is visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. This event is not observed by STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely an eruption and C6.3 flare from Active Region 14351 (S05W27) starting at 2026-01-25T10:25Z seen in SDO AIA 131/171/193/304 and GOES SUVI 131/171/195/284/304 imagery. Dimming is observed northwest of the eruption site in SDO AIA 193 imagery, indicating possibly northwestern deflection of this CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measured longitude based on the source location. As this event is not seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery, a triangulated measurement was not available to confirm possible deflection from the source. The measured parameters may vary slightly as a result.

cmes.note: Faint CME seen to the NE in GOES CCOR-1 and SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The CME is covered by a daily data gap in STEREO A COR2. A possible source is a faint, slow, medium-area eruption centered (N20E55) starting 2026-01-25T18:48Z, and seen in SDO AIA 193 as a faint, slowly developing dimming.

cmeAnalyses.note: A rather speculative, one-coronagraph (SOHO LASCO) analysis based on the possible source - a faint and slowly developing eruption seen in the NE of the solar disk in SDO AIA 193. The CME is fully covered by the daily gap in STEREO A COR2, so we are unable to confirm this analysis with triangulation.

cmes.note: CME with two fronts (possibly a faster shock and a slower bulk followed by multiple outflows) and seen to the SW in GOES CCOR-1 and SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The CME is overed by a daily data gap in STEREO A COR2. Its source is likely a notable eruption in and around AR 14345 (S17W66) seen starting at 2026-01-25T19:20Z in SDO AIA 193 as dimming, minor moving ejecta and opening of field lines on/close to the SW limb. There is also a long duration C3.1 flare from this AR peaking at 2026-01-25T20:25Z and likely associated with the post-eruptive arcades of this CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate, one-coronagraph (SOHO LASCO) analysis, based on the location of the source - flare and eruption in/around AR 14345. The CME is fully covered by the daily gap in STEREO A COR2, so we are unable to confirm this analysis with triangulation.
